Loop and back-edge rules:
- A sequence flow with `sourceRef == targetRef` is forbidden. Back-edges to earlier elements (a different `targetRef` that the process has already visited) are valid and required when the contract describes an iterative process.
- When a ContractBranch carries a `nextRef`, emit a sequence flow from the decision's gateway to the node with that id. If `nextRef` points to an earlier activity, this is the loop back-edge.
- For multi-exit loops (e.g. pass / no-progress / exhausted), emit ONE XOR gateway after the loop body with one outbound flow per branch â€” including the back-edge â€” not separate gateways per exit.

Parallel-gateway topology:
- Every PARALLEL fork MUST have a matching synchronising join: a second PARALLEL_GATEWAY node where every branch reconverges before downstream work proceeds. The join is a synthesised node with a stable unique id (e.g. `Gateway_join_<descriptor>`) and no `name`.
- After the join, emit a single outbound sequence flow to whatever comes next.

Inclusive-gateway topology:
- INCLUSIVE conditions are evaluated independently â€” any subset (including all) may fire concurrently. (Same `conditionExpression` shape as EXCLUSIVE, different semantics.)
- Every INCLUSIVE fork MUST have a matching synchronising join: a second INCLUSIVE_GATEWAY node. The join waits only for the branches that fired (unlike a parallel join, which waits for all branches). It's a synthesised node with a stable unique id and no `name`.
- A DEFAULT branch is permitted under INCLUSIVE â€” it fires only when no other branch's condition is true. The renderer writes the gateway's `default` attribute on the chosen outbound flow.
- After the join, emit a single outbound sequence flow to whatever comes next.

Embedded-subprocess topology:
- A `[SUB_PROCESS contains="a,b,c"]` contract activity becomes a `SUB_PROCESS` node with `triggeredByEvent=false`, id copied verbatim. Its members are the activities listed in `contains=`.
- Every member node listed in `contains=` MUST carry `parentRef` = the subprocess id, and every sequence flow between two members MUST also carry `parentRef` = the subprocess id. Members stay in the flat node list â€” nesting is expressed only by `parentRef`, not by physically moving them.
- Give the subprocess its own self-contained inner flow: emit one inner `START_EVENT` and one inner `END_EVENT` (both with `parentRef` = the subprocess id) and wire the members start-to-end between them.
- The subprocess node itself sits on the enclosing flow like any task: the main flow connects into the `SUB_PROCESS` node and out of it. Sequence flows connect to the subprocess node, not to its interior members â€” each flow keeps both endpoints on the same side of the boundary (both inside the subprocess or both outside).

Event-subprocess topology:
- An `[EVENT_SUBPROCESS trigger=â€¦ interrupting=â€¦ contains="a,b"]` contract entry becomes a `SUB_PROCESS` node with `triggeredByEvent=true`, id copied verbatim. Its members are the activities listed in `contains=`.
- Give it a typed inner start: one `START_EVENT` with `parentRef` = the event-subprocess id whose `eventDefinition` matches the trigger â€” MESSAGE â†’ `BpmnMessageEventDefinition` (+ a `definition.messages` entry), TIMER â†’ `BpmnTimerEventDefinition`, ERROR â†’ `BpmnErrorEventDefinition` (+ a `definition.errors` entry), ESCALATION â†’ `BpmnEscalationEventDefinition` (+ a `definition.escalations` entry), SIGNAL â†’ `BpmnSignalEventDefinition` (+ a `definition.signals` entry). Set that start's `isInterrupting` to the entry's interrupting flag.
- Every member node and every inner sequence flow carries `parentRef` = the event-subprocess id; wire the members start-to-end to one inner `END_EVENT` (also parentRef'd).
- An event subprocess has no incoming or outgoing sequence flow: it runs when its inner start fires, so it stays disconnected from the main flow rather than being wired into it.

Event-based-gateway topology:
- An EVENT_BASED decision becomes an `EVENT_BASED_GATEWAY` node. For each EVENT_GATEWAY branch, emit an `INTERMEDIATE_CATCH_EVENT` whose `eventDefinition` matches the branch `triggerKind`: TIMER â†’ `BpmnTimerEventDefinition` (expression from `triggerDetail`, an ISO-8601 duration); MESSAGE â†’ `BpmnMessageEventDefinition` pointing at a `definition.messages` entry named from `triggerDetail`; SIGNAL â†’ `BpmnSignalEventDefinition` pointing at a `definition.signals` entry named from `triggerDetail`.
- The gateway's only direct successors are those catch events â€” one outbound flow from the gateway to each catch event, and no activities directly between them. From each catch event, emit one flow to the branch's `nextRef`.
- The gateway is a pure wait: it has no join. Each branch proceeds independently after its event fires.

